{"id":"d=origam-topic-4283//p=e0787d47d33d4c5894be5f35e9159f43","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4283"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["e9021a6637b943da9263c2ac17e70e55"],"__file_part":["df78d58ed1e3418f8d9ff98b2347af92"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["4283"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/running-origam-server-in-docker-locally/4283"],"title":["Running ORIGAM Server in Docker Locally"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# Running ORIGAM Server in Docker Locally\n\nCategory: docs\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/running-origam-server-in-docker-locally/4283\n\n@jsusen (2025-10-29 14:59:00Z):\n   Running ORIGAM Server in Docker Locally \n This guide will walk you through the process of running official  ORIGAM docker images  of version 2025.11 or newer on your local machine for development or testing purposes. \n If you want to build and run your own image from ORIGAM source follow  this  guide. \n If you want to run an image earlier than 2025.11 look at  this guide . \n If you want to run an image earlier than 2025.3 look at  this guide . \n If you want to run an image earlier  than 2024.10 look at  this guide . \n   Prerequisites \n \n Docker installed on your system \n Basic knowledge of command-line operations \n \n You will also need an ORIGAM project (model) to run on the server. If you don\u2019t have one yet and just want to try things out you can use the  test model  included in the ORIGAM repository. This guide assumes you\u2019re working in the directory  C\\Origam\\MyProject\\Docker , but feel free to adjust the paths as needed for your setup. \n   Steps \n \n Create Environment File \n Run Docker Container \n \n   1. Create Environment File \n Create a new file named  demo.env  in your working directory (for example  C:\\Origam\\MyProject\\Docker ) with the following content: \n  OrigamSettings__DefaultSchemaExtensionId={main package id}\nOrigamSettings__DataConnectionString=\u0022Encrypt=False;Data Source={ip address of your db},1433;Initial Catalog={your db name};User ID={your db user};Password={your db user password};\u0022\nOrigamSettings__Name={your project name}\nCustomAssetsConfig__PathToCustomAssetsFolder=/home/origam/projectData/customAssets\nCustomAssetsConfig__RouteToCustomAssetsFolder=/customAssets\nDatabaseType=mssql\nExternalDomain_SetOnStart=https://localhost\nTZ=Europe/Prague\n  \n Then replace the placeholders \n \n \n  {ip address of your db} : Your database\u2019s IP address. For a local database, use  host.docker.internal  \n \n \n  {your db name} : Name of your new database (preferably your project\u2019s name) \n \n \n  {your db user} : Your database username \n \n \n  {your db user password} : Your database user password \n \n \n  {main package id} : ID of your project\u2019s main package. I you use the test model, the id is:  f17329d6-3143-420a-a2e6-30e431eea51d  \n \n \n  CustomAssetsConfig__PathToCustomAssetsFolder  is the path in the docker image where the custom assests folder will be mounted. The folder should cointain custom action icons for example. \n \n \n  CustomAssetsConfig__RouteToCustomAssetsFolder  is the route where the the client application can find the custom assets. \n \n \n  OrigamSettings__DataConnectionString  is a standard Microsoft SQL connection string. You can modify it how ever you like as long as it is valid. Note that you will have to specify how you want to deal with ecryption in the connection string. Details are  here . \n \n \n TZ: The time zone is set to \u2018TZ=Europe/Prague\u2019 by default, but can be changed to another. \n \n \n If you are running the server with Postgre SQL database, the   OrigamSettings__DataConnectionString  variable must me a valid postgres connection string. Note that the variable  OrigamSettings__DatabaseName  defines the database scheme (search path). \n  DatabaseType=postgresql\n  \n  Additional configuration  \n \n \n You can add any other variable from  OrigamSettings.config documentation  using the following notation: \n OrigamSettings__ ParameterName = Value  \n Example: \n OrigamSettings__HelpUrl= https://community.origam.com/  \n \n \n You can add also variables from  appsettings.json documentation  with this notation: \n  ElementName __ PropertyName = Value  \n Example: \n IdentityServerConfig__CookieExpirationMinutes=1440 \n \n Language settings example \n \n  LanguageConfig__Default=cs-CZ\nLanguageConfig__Allowed__0__Culture=cs-CZ\nLanguageConfig__Allowed__0__Caption=\u010Cesky\nLanguageConfig__Allowed__0__ResetPasswordMailSubject=Obnova Hesla\nLanguageConfig__Allowed__0__ResetPasswordMailBodyFileName=testResetPwFile.txt\n  \n \n \n   2. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00:23:05"},"vector":[0.010820322,-0.008259015,-0.062612675,0.015794637,-0.01957693,0.0003971995,-0.00821364,-0.054921165,-0.011312385,-0.0023077028,-0.0007727621,0.01825734,-0.031262003,-0.0041020275,0.028910976,-0.035315454,-0.02869855,0.03110783,0.020249892,0.018112035,0.009616495,-0.02874708,0.062188406,0.019666236,0.0026869564,0.018336717,-0.014046646,-0.037978556,0.0104559185,0.025076421,-0.021349698,-0.053674832,-0.027780917,-0.050039552,0.008288986,-0.00811782,0.011815353,0.030772014,-0.046647195,0.038984533,-0.012132864,-0.020612469,-0.018399687,0.054671098,-0.014633442,-0.04348033,0.037412107,0.002591309,0.026685093,-0.08749416,-0.028960647,-0.009018004,0.022532906,-0.06474749,0.04466871,0.052959397,-0.050326724,-0.02755379,-0.08025617,0.012191263,-0.001368296,0.008364486,-0.03899424,0.0075258883,-0.013312791,0.012533258,-0.00962684,0.015473079,-0.014114971,-0.027947646,-0.022559805,0.008244011,-0.06276215,-0.05516781,-0.07517183,0.01783429,0.018321725,-0.0033458634,-0.002019198,0.016669068,-0.017522203,0.002153685,0.046461515,-0.0050574,0.017965684,0.0034548654,-0.06454113,0.06728420